Interaction Between Age Group and Diabete Types

For this analysis, patients with either no diabetes or Type I or Type II diabetes are included (\(N=\) 92414). Recipient age are categorized, with the frequency in each category as shown below:

## 
##  [40,60)  [18,40)  [60,75) [75,100) 
##    44040    19212    27416     1746

We fit the Cox regression models for graft failure and patient death to check the interaction between age groups and the diabetes types. The reference group for age is 40 to 60 years old, and the reference for diabete type is Type II diabetes.

The related coefficients estiamtes for graft failure and for patient death are shown below. Note the signifiant negative estimate for DIAB.2_Type I:AGEC3[18,40) coefficient in the first table for graft failure. It implies in patients aged 18-40, Type II diabetes was a higher risk factor for graft failure than Type I diabetes. For other age groups, differences between the two types were not significant. No significant difference in the two diabetes types were found for patient death.

We also plot the hazard ratios (HR) for each combination of the age group and the diabetes types (status).

TOC

Time-Varying Effect of Diabetes

In this section, we only use the subset with non-missing diabetes (N = 94827).

To illustrate the time-varying effect of diabetes, we fit three Cox models (for graft failure and patient death separately) with various forms for the diabetes term (Yes vs. No)

  • a single time-invariant coefficient assuming proportionality;
  • a piecewise constant time-varying coefficient with cutting points at 3 months, 6 months, 1 year, 2 years, 3 years, 4 years and 5 years;
  • a smooth time-varying coefficient using natural cubic B-splines with 3 knots at the quartiles of the observed event times.

From both the piecewise constant fit and the smooth B-spline fit, the deviation from time-invariant effect estimate is obvious. The effect of diabetes starts low (0-3 months) when other risk factors may play a bigger role than later time; it then increases to a larger meganitude (and peaks round 1 year after TX); the diabetes effect comes down a little to a plateau after the first years after TX and then increases almost linearly again after hit the bottom around 2 and a half years after TX.

For the diabetes effect estimate for patient death after transplant, the waving trend is less apparent comapring to that of the graft failure. It almost increases linearly throughout out the first 5 years after TX and then reach a plateau around 0.6 (HR = 1.8).

TOC

Time-Varying Effect of Diabetes Types

In this section, we only use the subset with No diabetes or Type I or Type II Diabetes (N = 92414). We fit three Cox models to the data similarly as last section, with two time-varying coefficients (For No Diab and Diab I indicators) in the last two models.

For the graft failure, the estimated time-varying effect of No Diab is almost like the mirror image of that of the DiabYes in the previous section. However, the time-varying estimate for Diab I does not differ much from the time-invariant one, and neither is significantly different from zero.

For the patient death, the estimated effect of No Diab is decreasing over time after TX, but it is not very far from the time-invariant estimate. On the other hand there is no significant time-varying trend for the Diab I effect, showing a similar hazardous effect for both diabetes types.

We fit stratified Cox models with everything including the interaction between diabetes status (Yes or No (reference)) or diabetes types (Diab I, II vs. No) and dialysis time (TDIALC, Preemptive as the reference). We fit the models separately for living donors and deceased donors.

Preemptive kidney transplants on average have better suvival outcomes, but the benificial effects is smaller in meganitude for diabetic patients (indicated by negative interaction coefficient estimates), and there is no obvious diabetes type effects.

The related beta estiamtes are shown below (the raw outputs are in the last section).
